The Real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus of the Israelites from Egypt led by Moses.
I grew up with that.
The myth is easily told.
The Young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven from their bases in the south by Chiang Kai-sheks nationalist government in the early 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, roaring rivers, and rugged pasturelands, with Mao guiding the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope in the face of unimaginably poor prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, badly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they fought back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and established Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth correspond to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to search for his traces.
It remains a terrifying journey through regions that have changed little up to today, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I managed to locate 40 of them and spoke with them – they were ordinary people who had been left behind or had made it all the way to the end, but their stories were extremely revealing.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, no bigger than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought of deserting, but stayed, fearing he would be caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army of 86,000 soldiers had dwindled to 30,000.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
Yet no more than 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, fought at the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. It is said that 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of Nationalist troops, who were guarding the Luding Bridge with machine guns, thereby opening the way for the marching army.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu River was the most significant event of the Long March, and thus it is praised as such today.
However, documents I have reviewed suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu initially told a completely different story to the party historians. "The matter wasn't as complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should pay attention to the truth."
"How they are represented is another matter."
So the legend lives on.
There was merely a scuffle above the Dadu.
The local warlord, whom Chiang Kai-shek hated, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The marsh participants did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final goal.
When they came together in northern China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
Yet the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could scarcely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
The women were ordered to turn around and go back home because there wasn't enough food.
Just over a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the party decided that the Long March had to continue.
Yet she saved the kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek by the general Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
Not, however, for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's archrival, and were tasked with obtaining assistance from Russia across the western Chinese border.
Yet Mao sent them contradictory orders, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land, where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border; the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Nevertheless, she is absent from official historical records.
A Muslim commander took the senior officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
That was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny all the years she had dedicated to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were resolute, fought, starved, despaired, and endured.
Hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
The liquidations continued until practically no officers were left to command in the battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them through communist propaganda.
They endured their martyrdom with a courage and self-sacrifice that is unparalleled in the history of China and other peoples.
