What drove her to do that?
I interviewed one of the highest-ranking generals about what he knew about communism at that time. "I had no idea then, just as I don't now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself really knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, a hope for a just and progressive society.
No one perhaps – or could have known – how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice would be, and how enormous the difference between dream and reality would be.
